Consider the following news headline regarding Immigration Policy in the
    United States:

    \begin{center}
      \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{../images/q0004_fig1.png}
    \end{center}

    How will the effect of the current U.S.\ administration's proposed changes
    to the H-1B visa policy impact the welfare of the U.S workforce?

Consider a two-player game with the following payoffs. Each player has two
    strategies: Ana can choose Up or Down, while Bob can choose Left or Right.

    \vspace{8pt}
    \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}{cc|cc|}
      & & \multicolumn{2}{c|}{\textbf{Bob}} \\
      & & \textit{Left} & \textit{Right} \\
      \hline
      \multirow{2}{*}{\textbf{Ana}} & \textit{Up}   & 6,\ 6 & 0,\ 10 \\
                                    & \textit{Down} & 4,\ 0 & 1,\ \ 1 \\
      \hline
    \end{tabular}
    \end{center}
    \vspace{8pt}

    Ana and Bob only care about their own payoffs. However, in a coffee chat
    before the game, Bob was able to fake his intentions and make Ana think he
    is an altruistic person, that is, he equally cares about Ana's payoff as
    his own. What is the outcome of the game if Ana believes Bob's fake
    intentions?

solution:
Ana believes Bob has altruistic preferences, so she thinks Bob's utility
    is $U_\text{Bob} = \pi_\text{Bob} + \pi_\text{Ana}$.
    Ana re-evaluates Bob's payoffs accordingly:

    \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}{c|cc}
            & Left & Right \\
      \hline
      Up    & $6+6=12$ & $10+0=10$ \\
      Down  & $0+4=4$  & $1+1=2$   \\
    \end{tabular}
    \end{center}

    From Ana's perspective (believing Bob is altruistic):
    \begin{itemize}
      \item If Ana plays \textit{Up}: Bob prefers Left ($12 > 10$).
      \item If Ana plays \textit{Down}: Bob prefers Left ($4 > 2$).
    \end{itemize}
    $\Rightarrow$ Bob's dominant strategy (as Ana believes) is \textbf{Left}.

    Knowing Bob will play Left, Ana compares:
    \begin{itemize}
      \item Up + Left: Ana gets $\mathbf{6}$
      \item Down + Left: Ana gets $4$
    \end{itemize}
    $\Rightarrow$ Ana plays \textbf{Up}.

    Outcome: \textbf{(Up, Left)}. Note that in reality Bob would play Right
    (dominant strategy for the real payoffs), but Ana was deceived.
    Answer: \textbf{(A)}.

In year $t$, company $i$ charges $i^t$. The subsidy equals some $k^t$
    (for a randomly chosen company $k$). We need $a^t + b^t = k^t$ for
    some $a, b, k \in \{1, \ldots, 100\}$.

    \begin{itemize}
      \item \textbf{Year $t=1$:} We need $a + b = k$. Many solutions exist,
            e.g.\ $3 + 5 = 8$. \textbf{Possible.}
      \item \textbf{Year $t=2$:} We need $a^2 + b^2 = k^2$ (Pythagorean
            triples). Solutions exist, e.g.\ $3^2 + 4^2 = 5^2 = 25$, and
            $3, 4, 5 \leq 100$. \textbf{Possible.}
      \item \textbf{Year $t \geq 3$:} By Fermat's Last Theorem, there are
            \emph{no} positive integer solutions to $a^t + b^t = c^t$.
            \textbf{Impossible.}
    \end{itemize}

    Therefore, it is possible in exactly \textbf{2 years} ($t=1$ and $t=2$).
    Answer: \textbf{(C)}.

statement:
An analyst is evaluating two mutually exclusive investment projects,
    Project~A and Project~B. To compare them, the analyst has plotted their
    Net Present Value (NPV) profiles against a range of discount rates.

    \begin{center}
      \includegraphics[width=0.72\textwidth]{../images/q0010_fig1.png}
    \end{center}

    Based on the NPV profiles above, which of the following statements is
    correct?

solution:
At steady state, flows \emph{into} unemployment equal flows \emph{out}
    of unemployment:
    \[
      \underbrace{s \cdot (1 - u^*)}_{\text{employed} \to \text{unemployed}}
      = \underbrace{f \cdot u^*}_{\text{unemployed} \to \text{employed}}
    \]
    Solving for $u^*$:
    \[
      s - s u^* = f u^* \implies s = u^*(f + s)
      \implies \boxed{u^* = \frac{s}{s + f}}
    \]

    Intuition: a higher separation rate $s$ raises unemployment; a higher
    job-finding rate $f$ lowers it. Answer: \textbf{(B)}.

\textbf{Loan amount:} $PV = 500{,}000 \times (1 - 0.20) = \$400{,}000$

    \textbf{Parameters:} monthly rate $r = 6\%/12 = 0.5\% = 0.005$;
    $n = 30 \times 12 = 360$ payments.

    \textbf{Annuity formula:}
    \[
      \text{PMT} = PV \cdot \frac{r}{1-(1+r)^{-n}}
      = 400{,}000 \cdot \frac{0.005}{1 - (1.005)^{-360}}
    \]

    $(1.005)^{360} \approx 6.023$, so $(1.005)^{-360} \approx 0.1660$.

    \[
      \text{PMT} = 400{,}000 \cdot \frac{0.005}{1 - 0.1660}
      = 400{,}000 \cdot \frac{0.005}{0.8340}
      \approx 400{,}000 \times 0.005995
      \approx \mathbf{\$2{,}398}
    \]

    Closest answer: \textbf{\$2,400}. Answer: \textbf{(C)}.
